The central limit theorem states that if you take a large enough sample from any population, the sample mean will have an approximately Normal distribution with the mean being the same as the population and the standard deviation equal to the standard deviation of the population divided by the square root of the sample size. The standard deviation of the sample mean is known as the standard error of the sample mean.

English common words are called ‘stopwords’. To remove them type

chapter13 <-tm_map(chapter13,content_transformer(tolower))        # Convert all words to lowercase (else next step fails)
chapter13 <- tm_map(chapter13, removeWords, stopwords("english")) # remove the stopwords
